A Study on the Prevalence of Obesity, Cholesterol, Diabetes and Other Factors

Tan Guan San, Koo Tse Kain

17 Mar 2019

Data Science Project on Diabetes

Problem Statements

Diabetes is a chronic disease where the human body produces insufficient insulin to help the cells of the body use the glucose in food, resulting in high blood glucose level.

The disease has quadrupled over the last 35 years (WHO) In Singapore we have observed higher prevalence compared to other parts of the world.

  1. 9% in 1998 from 8.6% in 1992
  2. Cost > S$1.9bn in 2010 and
  3. Projected beyond S$2.5bn by 2050

Two types of diabetes:

  1. Type 1 - Genetic and unpreventable
  2. Type 2 - Related to weight - Body Mass Index(BMI), Waist-Hip Ratio(WHR), Frame.

Best Screening Test & Requirement:

  1. Fasting plasma glucose (HBA1C test or A1C) of which readings 6.5 and above are diagnosed as diabetics.
  2. Fasting time at least two hours and more (Postprandial Time) before the A1C test.

In our Capstone Project, we set to explore:

  1. Prevalence of diabetes is dependent on high body mass index, i.e. overweight and/or obese individuals have a higher risk of high glucose level.

  2. Females are more likely than males to have diabetes.

  3. Middle Age and Elderly persons (above 65 years old) have higher risk than Adults (below 40) to have Type 2 diabetes. Frame size and high glucose level are correlated positively.

  4. Co-morbidity of high cholesterols and high glucose level increase the risk of diabetes ie they have positive correlationship.

  5. Waist-to-hip ratio (WHR), an alternate classification of weight categories, is a more robust predictor on prevalence of diabetes.

Within the dataset, there is a Glycosylated Haemoglobin (glyhb) variable, which will serve as our dependent (continuous y) variable.

Also, the dataset contains various other independent variables like total cholesterol, height, weight, gender, frame, waist size, hip size which serves as our X variables (continous and discrete).

Out of the 8 variables, obesity is defined using Body Mass Index (BMI) measurements which is computed using the Weight and Height variables. Similiarly, Waist-Hip Ratio (WHR) is computed using Waist and Hip Sizes variables. These 2 new derived variables also serves as our independent variables (“X”).

We have 3 moderators as follows:

  1. First moderator (categorial x2), gender, is contained as follows: 0 being male; 1 being female.
  2. Second moderator (categorial x3), Age Group, is contained as follows: Age from 18 to 39 = Adult; Age from 40 to 65 = Middle; Age from 66 to 93 = Elderly.
  3. Third moderator (categorial x4), frame, is definded as follows: Small, Medium, Large.

Tidy & Transform

The first thing we did with our loaded dataset was to identify any invalid or incomplete observations and select valid cases (no missing observations).

Also, we performed the following:

  1. Rename these variables: time.ppn, stab.glu and bp. Replace “.” with “_“.
  2. Compute the BMI and WHR variables
  3. Categorise Age, BMI, WHR and Cholestorol into following groups: age into age_grp; bmi into bmi_grp, whr into whr_grp and chol into chol_grp
  4. With Postprandial Time (time_ppn) as the criteria, these dataframes are made: diabetes120 : contains records for time_ppn > 120 minutes diabetes480 : contains records for time_ppn between 120 to 480 minutes

Statistical Analysis: ANOVA 1-factor

We conducted ANOVA 1-factor analysis for the 3 datasets with these objectives:

  1. Signifcant difference between dataset 1 and dataset 2 statistically
  2. Interaction of moderators and Frame with BMI on A1C Results for dataset 3
###   Statistical  
##    ANOVA One-Factor

aov_m1<- aov(glyhb ~ bmi_grp, data = diabetes)
summary (aov_m1)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## bmi_grp       3   55.6  18.527   3.822 0.0102 *
## Residuals   365 1769.2   4.847                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#   Need to do Post-Hoc test as the p-value = 0.0102 which is less than 0.05,
#   indicating there is a signficant different between group means
#   Post-Hoc test to explore where the difference come from among 
#   the 4 bmi groups. Use Tukey's Honest Signifcant Difference (HSD)

TukeyHSD(aov_m1, which = "bmi_grp", ordered = FALSE)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = glyhb ~ bmi_grp, data = diabetes)

## OB-UW 1.1396267 -0.920855631 3.200109 0.4829848
## OW-NW 0.7945268 -0.003221573 1.592275 0.0513791
## OB-NW 0.8971407  0.140543838 1.653737 0.0126481
## OB-OW 0.1026139 -0.592570196 0.797798 0.9811572
#   The significant difference comes from group OB_NW with p = 0.033 < 0.05.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))

Our hypothesis is that female has higher risk of contracting diabetes than males

We used boxplot and Mean plot with t-test to determine the validity of the hypothesis.

#   Test based on Gender
#   Bartlett test - test homogeneity variance for assumption to decide which 
#   t-test to use.

bartlett.test(glyhb ~ gender, data = diabetes480)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  glyhb by gender
## Bartlett's K-squared = 1.1476, df = 1, p-value = 0.2841
##  data:  glyhb by gender
##  Bartlett's K-squared = 1.1476, df = 1, p-value = 0.2841

# p-value = 0.284: use var.equal = T for t.test

t.test(glyhb ~ gender, var.equal = T, data = diabetes480)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  glyhb by gender

Model 5: To ascertain WHR is a better predictor than BMI

Finally, we want to know whether WHR is a better predictor than BMI since its mean spread for High Risk Group is much higher than those of BMI Groups. Three moderators included are Frame, Gender and Age.

We first define the two competing hypotheses:

  1. H0: WHR is a better predictor than BMI
  2. HA: WHR is not better predictor than BMI

Next we visualise using the co-relation matrix. After which, we created two models one for BMI and one for WHR and using ANOVA to compare which is a better predictor. Further analysis using standardized regression coefficients.

###########################################################################
##    Modeling : Model and Specify OLS model
##    Question 5 : Investigate if Waist-to-hip ratio (WHR) is a better 
##    predictor than BMI on the prevalence of diabetes
###########################################################################

#Set gender: 0 being male; 1 being female

diabetes480_cor <- diabetes480 %>% 
  mutate(glyhb_m=rowMeans(diabetes480 %>% dplyr::select(glyhb)),
         bmi_m=rowMeans(diabetes480 %>% dplyr::select(bmi)),
         whr_m=rowMeans(diabetes480 %>% dplyr::select(whr)),
         fem=ifelse(gender == "male",0,1),
         smallf=ifelse(frame == "small",0,1))

## Created and ran a correlational matrix, to see how our variables of interest (within the model) are related.

diabetes480_cor %$% 
  cor(tibble(fem, smallf, age, glyhb_m, bmi_m, whr_m)) %>%
  round(.,2)

Analysis:

  1. Correlogram indicates that WHR has a significant correlation with A1C test result whereas the BMI coefficient is insignifcantly correlated to A1C Test Result. Comparing with frame, BMI has a higher corelation than WHR.

  2. Comparing both models using ANOVA method (Model 1 using BMI, Model 2 using WHR), model 1 is a better fit model. The adjusted R-squared in model 1 is also slightly higher. However, WHR has a much higher unstandardized Coefficient value. Similar results are observed with frame included (Model 3 and 4).

  3. Adding frame to the BMI model (i.e. model 3) suggested improvements to the model.

  4. Using standardized coefficients regression yields very small differences in standard coefficient values bewteen BMI and WHR (0.10 versus 0.09).

From the above results, basing on these 2 analysis methods, the evidence shown is not convincing enough to accept the null hypothese (H0), i.e. it is not sufficient to prove that WHR is a much better predictor than BMI for prevalence of diabetes. It needs to be further analysed in conjunction with other residual plots, visualisation plots and other model statistics.

Interpretation of the Results

From our data science project, we could find the following findings:

  1. It is imperative to adhere to the Postprandial time (Fasting Period) of between two hours to eight hours for an effective detection of diabetes for those in the high risk group.

  2. Age rather than gender has a positive influence on the prevalence of diabetes.

  3. There is a some indication of corelation between a person’s frame and A1C Result.

  4. High cholesterol is positively correlated with high A1C Result indicating the high risk of being a diabetics.

Implications

  1. Co-morbidity of other chronic illness, such as high cholesterol, can increase the risk of diabetes hence it is imperative to seek continuous treatment for those who are diagnosed and regular medical follow up so as to mitigate the risk.

  2. Ageing has an impact of psycho-social and physical well-being of an individual and increase his or her risk of Type 2 diabetes. With the fast ageing population, policy and/or program that could drive and support prevention healthcare with encouragement of healthy lifestyle could reduces the risk of dieases that contributing to diabetes and/or diabetes itself.

Limitations and Future Directions

  1. In the medical domain, frame categories are determined by a person’s wrist circumference in relation to his/her height. It is also gender dependent. Since the wrist circumference is unknown, hence, it limits our ability to verify the validity of the classification and analysis of its influence on the A1C Test Result.

  2. Ethnicity may be a factor that can affect the prevalence of diabetes as there are significant differences in biological and psycho-social amongst the difference ethnic groups which may influence the lifestyle factors. Thus the limitation of using only African American to extrapolate the same effect on other ethnic group may not be accurate. Future direction for such research should include a good representative samples of other ethnic groups, such as Caucasian or Asian, for a more robust analysis.

  3. Does geographic variation also play a part in the prevalence of diabetes? This study sample is only limited to 2 locations in central Virginia for African Americans. The study can potentially be expanded to other U.S states and further to the East and Asian regions.

  4. Lifestyle modifications like diet and exercise is effective at reducing the incidence of Type 2 Diabetes and improving glycemic control, even without a significant reduction in body weight. Thus, it is unclear whether weight loss, through lifestyle modification, is a cornerstone for improving glycemic control in individuals with prediabetes. Further trials can be executed with diet and exercise data included on the testers for further analysis.

  5. High blood pressure, or hypertension, is a condition that’s seen in people with Type 2 diabetes. It’s unknown why there’s such a significant relationship between the two diseases. We can explore deeper on this and ascertain if diet, exercise, obesity plays a signifcant part on this corelationship.
